<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-567-691  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 567 691.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  Nov 12 1990 n3187 p58(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A chilling new era for Philips - and Europe. (white-collarlayoffs) (Philips Gloeilampenfabrieken N.V.) (InternationalBusiness - The Netherlands)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kapstein, Jonathan; Levine, Jonathan; Schares, Gail E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sales and production are down at many of PhilipsGloeilampenfabrieken N.V.'s plants.andP;  The computer and electronicindustries leader in the Netherlands and Europe plans to reduceits global workforce by 45,000 jobs through layoffs, firings andjob elimination.andP;  The productivity rate of Philips and similarEuropean companies such as Siemens is lower than the foreigncompetition, especially from Japan.andP;  In addition, the personnelcosts of these firms are much greater.andP;  For Philips, even theusually lucrative lighting division is doing poorly.andP;  The $1.1billion loss Philips is reporting for the first nine months of FY1990 means massive cutbacks for white-collar personnel and theinstitution of specific performance goals for managers for thefirst time.andP;  This changes an old tradition of lifetime jobsecurity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Philips Gloeilampenfabrieken N.V. (Layoffs).andO;Topic:     Work Force ReductionComputer industryElectronic IndustryLayoffEuropeNetherlands.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>